India's New Hope
The latest elections in Cambridge, US – India may be the most important positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost always ruled India since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be happy with this decision.
The head of the Congress Party, former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's widow, Sonia Gandhi, has been de facto ruling since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh is just a puppet.
Under her leadership, the National Democratic Alliance pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led to India's economic growth rate dipping below 4% in 2013.
The per capita GDP still hovered around $4,000, less than half of China's.
Newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised rapid growth in employment and income for the whole of India, just as he had done as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with economic activity expanding and attracting business investments from within and outside India.
One of the key features of the latest election was the BJP, Modi's Indian People's Party, winning an absolute majority in the National Parliament, a rare achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties in order to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will help Modi with his economic plan.
New Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has rich political experience, having served as a minister in the previous Bharatiya Janata Party government.
Jaitely is also known for his strategy of sympathizing with commercial interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (central bank).Rajan is an outstanding economist who, in his tenure as Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, has shown a desire to lower India's high double-digit inflation rate and has attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
Measures needed to stimulate economic growth require time to be implemented and produce results.
If you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine the progress made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small part of the population can get the opportunities provided by these institutions, because primary and secondary education in India is far behind.
About 60% of Indian adults have the literacy level of primary school.
Teachers themselves have a poor educational background, and their work motivation is also insufficient. Many teachers do not even appear at the schools they are teaching at.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
Recent expansions of private air routes and airports indicate that private enterprises can also make a difference in this field.
Fiscal integration.
Large-scale budget deficits are absorbing people's savings, and the money should be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits have led to an increase in the national debt that can only be financed through future taxation.
Privatization.
The government-owned manufacturing enterprises and other industries in India are inefficient, often resulting in the consumption of people's savings.
Selling these enterprises can directly help to accelerate economic growth.
��Eliminate subsidies.
Power and energy subsidies have led to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although it is difficult to cancel these subsidies politically, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, due to the introduction of a prominent fingerprint-based cash transfer new system, the efficiency of cash transfer payments in India is high.
Reform of agriculture.
Under the current system. The government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
As a result, large quantities of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives are misled.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Ownership and zoning.
Just visit Mumbai or other major Indian cities, you will see that zoning restrictions lead to poor urban land use and hinder urban development.
Lack of clear property rights, especially agricultural land rights, hinder industrialization in rural areas.
Relax restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign companies cannot become the controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions can strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex national and state sales tax system has distorted domestic trade.
Discussions on replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a dual tax system have been going on for a long time, and it's now time to implement them.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases have destroyed economic confidence, and have also hindered official decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by small-scale corruption, with bribery becoming a common feature of all commercial and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and restrict small-scale corruption through new cash transfer payment systems.
Driven by strong growth and expected profit increases, the Indian stock market has risen 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their election promises.
